This analysis detects returning pointers/references to stack-allocated objects.
1. What object address/reference is returned?
2. Is the object local stack storage, static storage, or heap storage?
3. Could macro expansion or wrapper APIs change storage duration semantics?
4. Is the returned value consumed by callers in ways that can dereference dangling memory?
Use the tools to confirm storage duration and escape path.
If the returned object has valid lifetime after return, there is no issue.
Only flag if a stack object escapes function scope.
